{
  "doc_id": "57933",
  "text": "A major similarity between the two anamniote model organisms is the pivotal early role of the canonical Wnt/b-catenin signaling pathway in dorsal determination. After fertilization, a dorsal determinant, Wnt11 in frogs [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and wnt8 mRNA in fish [CITATION_3] , is transferred from the vegetal part of the oocyte to the future dorsal side. In zebrafish this process is mediated by an active, microtubule-dependent process [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] and results in the activation of canonical Wnt/b-catenin signaling on the presumptive dorsal side. Consequently, the dorsal transcriptional network is activated, which will ultimately lead to the expression of BMPantagonists and the formation of the BMP-signaling gradient across the DV-axis. This activity gradient will have powerful patterning effects across the ectoderm and the mesoderm [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
